b'' b'accounts of anti-armenian human right violations in azerbaijan b'prelude to current events in nagorno-karabakh' b'' b'+---------------------------------------------------------+' b'| b'| i saw a naked girl with her hair down. they were b'| dragging her. she kept falling because they were b'| pushing her and kicking her. she fell down, it was b'| muddy there, and later other witnesses who saw it from b'| their balconies told us, they seized her by the hair b'| and dragged her a couple of blocks, as far as the b"| mortgage bank, that's a good block and a half or two b'| from here. i know this for sure because i saw it b'| myself. b'| b'+---------------------------------------------------------+' b'' b'' b'deposition of tatyana mikhailovna arutunian (nezhintseva)' b'' b'born b'train conductor' b'azerbaijani railroad' b'' b'resident at building apartment b'microdistrict no. b'sumgait [azerbaijan]' b'' b"i hadn't lived very long in sumgait, only eight years. i moved there from" b'novosibirsk. my son entered the baku nautical school, and so i transferred' b'to azerbaijan. later i met someone and married him, and now my name is' b"arutunian, my husband's name b'' b'that there would be a massacre was not discussed openly, but there were hints' b'and gibes, so to speak, at the armenian people, and they were mocking the' b'russians, too. i was constantly aware of it at work, and not just this past' b"year. i couldn't find a definite place for myself in the pool at work because" b"i, i'll just say it, couldn't steal, couldn't deceive, and couldn't be" b'involved in bribe-taking. and when i asked for decent working conditions they' b'told me, "leave, don\'t keep the others from working, you aren\'t cut out for' b'this kind of work." and at work and around all the time i would hear gibes at' b'the armenians, like "the turks had it right, they killed them all--the way' b'they\'ve multiplied here they\'re making it hard for us to live," and "things' b'will be just fine if we get rid of them all." "no problem, the turks will' b'help," they say, "if we ask them, they\'ll rid armenia of armenians in half an' b'hour." well that\'s the way it all was, but i never thought, of course that it' b"would spill over into a bloody tragedy, because you just couldn't imagine it." b"here we've been living under the soviet government for years, and no one" b'even considered such an idea possible.' b'' b'but i had been forming my own opinions, and in the presence of authoritative' b'people i would often ask, "where is this all leading, do people really not see' b'what kind of situation is emerging here. the russians are fleeing sumgait,' b"there are very few of them left. why is no one dealing with this, what's going" b'on?" and when it all happened on the 27th and 28th, it became clear that' b'everything had been arranged by someone, because what else are you to make of' b'it if the first secretary of the city party committee is marching ahead of the' b"demonstration with an azerbaijani flag? i wouldn't be saying this now if i" b"hadn't received personal confirmation from him later. because when we were" b'under guard in the sk club on the 1st, he came to the club, that muslimzade.' b'the women told me, "there he is, there he is, that\'s muslimzade." i didn\'t' b'believe the rumors that he had carried an azerbaijani flag. i thought that' b'they were just false rumors. i went over to him and said, "are you the first' b'secretary of our city party committee?" he answers me, "yes." and i ask him,' b'"tell me, did you really march ahead of that gang carrying an azerbaijani' b"flag, and behind you they were carrying denigrating signs, i don't know" b'exactly what they said, but there was mention of armenian blood?" and he tells' b'me, "yes, i was there, but i tried to dissuade them from it." then i asked him' b'another question: "and where were you when they were burning and slaughtering' b'us? and he said, "i. we didn\'t know what to do, we didn\'t know, we didn\'t' b'anticipate that that would happen in sumgait."' b'' b'comrade mamedov, the first deputy chairman of the council of ministers of the' b'azerbaijani ssr, answered the same question for me: "no, we actually didn\'t' b'anticipate the slaughter in sumgait. at that time we were trying to contain' b'the crowd of in baku that was preparing for a massacre." those are his' b'exact words, the ones he said in the office of the council of ministers of the' b'armenian ssr.' b'' b"and now, about the events themselves. of course it's painful to discuss them," b"because it may seem that it's not true to someone else. various rumors" b"concerning what happened are making the rounds: some are true, others aren't." b'but unfortunately there are more true ones than false, because it was so' b'horrible: in our age, here in the space age, the age of science, the age of' b"progress, i don't know, if someone had told me this story, if i were living in" b"or around moscow, i wouldn't have believed it. why not? because it was really" b"a genocide, it was a massacre. that's genuinely what it was." b'' b"for example, on that day, the 28th--i didn't know about the 27th because my" b'husband and i were both sick, both of us had the flu, and we were in bed--on' b'the 28th our neighbor comes to our place and says, "you\'re in bed? you don\'t' b'know anything about it? there was a demonstration in town, and after it they' b'were overturning armenian cars and burning them. they were looking into cars' b"and asking, 'are you an armenian?' if they answered in armenian, then they" b'turned the car over and burned it." this isn\'t made up, the wife of the senior' b'investigator of the baku ministry of internal affairs told us. he was' b"returning home from his dacha with his wife, raisa sevastyanova, she's my" b'neighbor. she immediately came and told lis that they had landed right in the' b"middle of it, i don't know what to call it, the cavalcade of automobiles they" b'were stopping. he answered in azerbaijani, they let them go, but they made him' b"honk the horn, they were kicking up a fracas. we didn't even believe it, and" b'i said, "certainly that didn\'t happen, how can that be?" and she said,' b'"muslimzade was leading the crowd, and the sputnik store was completely' b'smashed because most of the salespeople there are armenians. and when he saw' b'that they had started breaking the glass in that store, he said, "don\'t break' b"the shop windows, don't destroy state property, but do whatever else you want." b'" i didn\'t hear this with my own two ears, but it is a fact that the store was' b'torn up and the director of the store was beaten for employing armenians' b"although he's an azerbaijani." b'' b'while we were talking, all of a sudden right across from us sevastyanova' b'is the first to look out the window and say, "look, there\'s a crowd out' b'there." and sure enough, when we looked out there we saw that the crowd had' b'already started wrecking the neighboring building. there was an armenian' b"family there, a woman and two girls. they lived across from us. i'm sorry, i" b"don't know the building number or the people's names, since we were in my" b"husband's apartment, in microdistrict and i lived in microdistrict no. b'there was awful looting going on there at the time, the most hideous things' b'were going on there then. one building there, ours, was attacked twice, once' b"wasn't enough for them. they returned to the places where they hadn't finished" b'the armenians off. if an azerbaijani family dared to conceal armenians, they' b'beat the azerbaijanis too. they also beat russians, if it was russians doing' b'the hiding. because there were russians among them, they said so on' b"television, there were people of various nationalities. but they didn't tell" b"us why there were people of different nationalities. because they wouldn't" b"have touched the azerbaijanis if they hadn't dared to stick up for the" b'armenians and give them temporary shelter in their homes.' b'' b'at the time i saw this from the window i was there, sevastyanova was there,' b'and so was my husband. we went out onto the balcony and saw a television fly' b'off a balcony. all kinds of things, even a sofa. then, when it was all down' b'there, they burned it up. then we saw the crowd, and they were all oohing. at' b"first i couldn't figure out what was happening. and later i told my husband," b'"lendrush, l think they\'re beating someone out there." and he answered, "i' b'don\'t know, could be." suddenly the crowd separated for a moment, and i saw' b'it, and raisa sevastyanova saw it too. my husband had turned the other way,' b"he didn't see it. i saw a naked girl with her hair down. they were dragging" b'her. she kept falling because they were pushing her and kicking her. she fell' b'down, it was muddy there, and later other witnesses who saw it from their' b'balconies told us, they seized her by the hair and dragged her a couple of' b"blocks, as far as the mortgage bank, that's a good block and a half or two" b'from here. i know this for sure because i saw it myself.' b'' b'then the crowd rushed toward our building. we were standing there, and you can' b'of course imagine what we were feeling. were they going to kill us or not? and' b'i also had the awful thought that they might torment me the way they tormented' b'that woman, because i had just seen that.' b'' b'i asked my husband. i gave him an axe and said, "you kill me first, and then' b'let them do what they want with the corpse." but our neighbors, it\'s true,' b'defended us, they said, "there aren\'t any armenians in our entryway, go away,' b'only muslims live here." disaster missed us that time.' b'' b"but at two o'clock in the morning a crowd of about people, approximately," b"came back to our place. my husband was already asleep. he can sleep when he's" b"upset about something, but i can't. i was standing, running from balcony to" b"balcony. our power was out, i don't remember for how long, but it was as" b'though it had been deliberately turned off. there were no lights whatsoever,' b'and i was glad, of course. i thought it was better that way. but then i look' b'and the crowd is at our balcony. this was at in the morning. the first' b'time they were at our building it was and now it was in the' b'morning. but i never thought that that old woman on the first floor, the' b'azerbaijani, was awake and watching out, there were human beings among them' b'too. so she goes out with a pail of garbage, as though she needed to be taking' b"garbage out at two o'clock in the morning. she used it as a pretext and went" b'toward those young people. they really were youngsters. from my balcony you' b'could see perfectly that they were young azerbaijani boys. they spoke' b'azerbaijani. and when they came up to her she said, "what do you want?" and' b'they answered, "we want the armenian family that lives here" [pointing toward' b'the second floor with their hands]. she says, "i already told you, we don\'t' b'have any armenians here, now leave, do you hear, this is an old muslim woman' b'talking to you," and grabbed the hand of one boy who was trying to walk around' b'her and enter the building anyway and started pushing him away. and so they' b'seemed to listen to her. they were all very young, they started apologizing' b'and left. that was the second time death was at our door.' b'' b'i forgot to mention about one other apartment, a man named rubik lives there,' b"i don't know him really, i knew his daughter, i mean i saw her around, but we" b"really didn't know them. but i do know that that guy who lives on the fourth" b'floor across from our entryway went to chernobyl and worked there for eight' b'months, to earn money. can you imagine what that means? he risked his life to' b'earn x amount of money in order to better his family. he bought new furniture' b"and was getting ready to give his daughter's hand in marriage, but, alas," b'everything was ruined by those creeps and scoundrels. they threw everything' b'out the windows, and the rest we saw from our balcony: how the neighbors on' b'the left and right ran into the apartment and carried off everything that' b"hadn't already been smashed or taken. what is one to think of that? it means" b'that the parents in those families were in on it too. unfortunately i came to' b'be of the opinion that it was all organized and that everything had been' b'foreseen in advance: both the beating of the armenians and the stripping of' b'apartments. something on the order of "we\'ll move the armenians out and take' b'over their apartments."' b'' b'i have worked honestly my whole life, you can check everything about me. i' b'came as a patriot from china, waited for nights on end in front of the' b'consulate general of the ussr, i came to my homeland as a patriot because i' b'knew that the party and the komsomol were holy things. but when i saw in' b"sumgait that there wasn't anything holy about them, that party membership was" b'bought, that komsomol members joined only for personal gain, that there were' b'no ideals, no ideas, god save me, everything was being bought and sold, i saw' b'all of it and understood how they could allow that crap to go on like it did.' b'' b"i can't talk any more about it the image of that beating when i" b'went out of my own apartment--they picked us up under soviet army guard, they' b'had arrived from all over to suppress that gang--not only armenians, but some' b'russian families and their children, too, came out of their apartments and' b'joined us, because no normal person who had seen that could stay there with' b"the situation the way it was. and what's interesting is that when we left on" b'the buses i rode and thought that at least one group of people, for sure' b'people would basically rise to the situation, would have some compassion for' b'the armenians, would somehow understand the injustice of what was done. but' b'having analyzed and weighed the whole thing, once i calmed down, having' b'thought it all through, i came to a conclusion that is shared by many people.' b"if a lot of azerbaijanis didn't want their armenian neighbors to be killed," b'and that basically depended on that muslimzade--he said that he had wanted to' b"calm them down--then is it possible that he didn't have people at hand to whom" b'he could whisper at the last minute, "go and announce it on television:' b"citizens of sumgait! take what you can into your hands, let's protect our" b'neighbors from this massacre?" those crowds weren\'t such that there was no' b"controlling them. basically they were unarmed. they didn't have firearms," b'mostly they had knives, they had all kinds of metal parts, like armature' b'shafts, sharpened at the ends, special rocks, different to a degree that we' b"noticed them: there aren't rocks like those in sumgait soils, they were" b'brought from somewhere, as though it were all specially planned. so as i was' b'saying, i weighed it all out and if any of our neighbors had wanted to defend' b"us, why wasn't it arranged? it means that the government didn't want to do" b'it. when the crowd was moving from the city party committee to the sputnik,' b'what, there was no way of informing baku? no, there was no way, it turns out!' b"the crowd was doing violence in our microdistrict. i won't mention the things" b"i didn't see myself, i'll only talk about the things i myself witnessed. they" b"were in microdistrict beginning at o'clock in the evening, when i saw them" b'from the other building, and they were somewhere else until mid-night or one' b"o'clock in the morning, because at they came back to our building. they" b"hadn't completely finished making their predatory rounds of microdistrict b'when they returned to our building i told my husband, "lendrush, now the' b'police are probably going to come, my god, now the authorities are probably' b'going to find out and come to our aid." well, alas, no, there were to be no' b'authorities, not a single policeman, not a single fireman, not a single' b'ambulance came while they were raging, as it turns out, as we later found out,' b'beginning on the might of the 27th. there were dead people, ruined apartments,' b'and burned autos: one car near the bus station, it was burned and overturned,' b'it was probably there about four days, everyone saw it and what went on in' b'block those who live there know, they saw from their balconies how they' b'attacked the soldiers in the buses, how they beat those poor, unarmed' b"soldiers, and how on that square, i can't remember the name of it, where there" b"is that fork coming from the bus station, that intersection, now i'm upset and" b"i can't think of the name there's a tall building there, a 9-story, and" b'from the balconies there people saw that butchery, when the poor soldiers,' b'wearing only helmets, with shields and those unfortunate clubs, moved against' b'that mob. and when they fell, those 12-to 14-year-old boys ran up and using' b'stones, big heavy stones, beat them to death on their heads. who could have' b'guessed that something like that could happen in the soviet union and under' b'the soviet government? the upshot is that this republic has not been under' b'soviet control for a long time, but no one wanted to pay any attention or get' b'involved.' b'' b'if you were to go and ask at my work many people would confirm that i tell the' b"truth, i've been struggling for truth for five years there already, the five" b'years that i worked at the azerbaijani railroad. some people there considered' b"me a demagogue, others who knows what; some think i'm an adventure seeker, and" b'some, a prankster. but i wanted everything to be right, i would become' b'outraged: how can this be, why is it people treat one another this way on a' b'soviet railroad, as though the azerbaijani railroad were azerbaijani property,' b'or the property of some magnate, or some "mafia": if i want to, i\'ll get you' b"out of here; if i want to, i'll get rid of you; if i want to, i'll do" b"something else? and there's a black market price for everything, in the most" b'brazen way: a coach to moscow costs so much, a coach on a local train costs so' b"much. once when i was complaining to the head of the conductor's pool, he had" b"the nerve to tell me, maybe you won't even believe this, but this, i'm afraid," b'i heard with my own ears: "tatyana, just how long can you fight for something' b"that you know will never have any effect? you're alone against everyone, so" b"instead why don't you give more money to the chief conductor, and everything" b'will go fine for you." i started to cry, turned, and left. what else could i' b'do, where else could i go to complain? i realized that everything was useless.' b'and the root of the whole thing is that it all goes on and no one wants to see' b'it. i filed a written complaint, and they ground it into dust, they destroyed' b"it, i still have a copy, but what's the use? when the general procuracy got" b'involved with the investigation of the bloody sumgait affair, in addition to' b'the information about what i saw, what i was a witness to, i gave testimony' b"about the mafia at the railroad. they accepted my petition, but i don't know" b"if they're going to pursue it or not. because, you'll excuse me, i no longer" b"believe in the things i aspired to, the things i believed in before: it's all" b'dead. they just spit on my soul, stomped on everything, physically, and most' b"important, spiritually, because you can lose belongings, that's nonsense, that" b'all comes with time, but when your soul is spit upon and when the best in' b'you--your beliefs--are destroyed, it can be very difficult to restore them...' b'' b"i want to tell of one incident. i just don't know, at the time i was in such a" b"state that i didn't even take minor things into account. here is an example." b"of course, it's not a minor one. my neighb