n' b'apartments in the building, they went here and there and looked, and saw that' b'the windows were intact, and so they calmed down. but even though the windows' b'in that apartment were not broken, everything inside was totally smashed, and' b'vitalik lay there with a broken skull, and his mother and father had already' b"been murdered. little vitalik didn't even know they were dead. so two weeks" b"ago, i don't know, he was in critical condition, no, maybe it was longer: we" b'left sumgait on march spent some time in moscow, and then we came to' b"yerevan. so it's been about a month already; it's so hard to keep all this" b"straight. so valery, the next day, when he found out that vitalik's family has" b'been killed and vitalik was ling in the semashko hospital in baku, valery and' b"his classmates got together and went to visit him. but they wouldn't admit" b'them, telling them that he was in critical condition and that he was still in' b'a coma. they cried and left, having also found out that the girl i saw being' b'kicked and dragged was in that hospital too. as it turns out she was brought' b'there in serious condition, but at least she was alive at the time b'' b'when we got to the sk club we would see first one friend and then another,' b'throw ourselves into their arms and kiss them, because you had wondered if' b'these friends were alive or not, if those friends were alive or not and' b'when you saw them you were so glad to find out that the family had lived! when' b'you saw people you heard things that made your hair stand on end.' b'' b'if you publish everything that happened it will be a hideous book. a book of' b'things it is even difficult to believe. and those two girls who were raped' b"were entirely black and blue, the ones at the sk, they know i'm not lying," b'that girlfriend came up to one of them and said, "what happened?" and she' b'bared her breasts, and they were completely covered in cigarette burns b'those rogues had put cigarettes out on her breasts. after something like that' b"i don't know how you can live in a city and look at the people in it." b'' b'now when we stayed at the military unit for a while, they provided,' b'well, basic conditions for us there. the military unit is located in nasosny,' b'some six miles from sumgait. and living there we met with a larger group' b'of people. there were about people at the unit. you know, there was a' b"point when i couldn't even go outside because if you went outside you saw" b'so much heartbreak around you. and when you hear the false rumors b'' b'yes, by the way, false rumors were spread in sumgait saying that the armenians' b'around yerevan had destroyed azerbaijani villages and razed them to the ground' b"with bulldozers. i didn't know whether to believe it or not. and people who" b"don't know any better get the idea that it was all done in revenge. but when" b'i arrived in armenia and was in spitak, and in spitak all those villages are' b'not only intact, but at that time had even been protected just in case, they' b'were guarded, they got better food than did the inhabitants of spitak. not a' b'single person there died, and no one is planning to harm them. around yerevan' b"all the villages are safe and unharmed, and the armenians didn't attack" b'anyone. but actually, after an evil of the magnitude suffered in sumgait there' b"could have been a feeling of vengefulness, but no one acted on it. and i don't" b'know why you sometimes hear accusations to the effect that the armenians are' b'guilty, that it is they who organized it. rumors like that are being spread in' b'azerbaijan. and if one old person says it and ten young ones hear it, they not' b'only perceive it with their minds, but with their hearts, too. to them it' b'seems that the older person is telling the truth. for example, one says; "did' b'you know that out of people killed (by the way, originally they said b'people, but later they found a 32nd), were azerbaijani and one was an' b'armenian?"' b'' b"of course i'm upset, but it's utterly impossible to discuss such things and" b'not become upset. sometimes l forget things, but i know i want to return to' b'the time when we were in the sk club across from the city party committee.' b'when i saw muslimzade in the sk club building i went to him to ask because i' b"couldn't believe that he had marched in the front carrying a banner. i already" b'mentioned this, and if i repeat anything, please excuse me. i asked him, "why' b'did you do that and why are you here now, why did you come here? to laugh at' b'these women who are strewn about on the floor?" the overcrowding there was' b'tremendous, it was completely unsanitary, and several of the children were' b"already sick. it's true the troops tried to make it livable for us. they" b'cooked for us on their field stoves and provided us with wonderful food, but' b'the thing is that their main job was to ferret out the gang that was still at' b'it everywhere, that was continuing its sordid affairs everywhere. plus they' b"were never given any direct orders, they didn't know what they were authorized" b"to do and not to do. and it was only on march at five o'clock in the evening" b'that krayev himself, the lieutenant general, the city commandant of sumgait,' b'was given full authority and told everyone over a microphone from an armored' b'personnel carrier that now he could do what he wanted to do, as his heart' b'advised him, and relocate people to the military unit.' b'' b"but that's not what i want to talk about now. muslimzade, characteristically," b'tried to get me out of the sk building and take me to the city party' b'committee, which is across the square from the club. he took me by the' b'hand and said, "citizen, don\'t worry, we\'ll go and have a talk in my office.' b'i told him, "no, after everything you\'ve done, i don\'t believe one iota of' b"what you say. if i go to the city party committee i'll disappear, and the" b'traces of me will disappear too. because you can\'t stand it when oh' b'yes, and there was another interesting detail from that meeting. it was even' b"very funny, although at the time i wasn't up to laughing. he was in a nice," b'expensive hat, and so as to put him to shame, so to speak, i said, "oh, why' b'did you come here all duded up like a london dandy, you smell of good perfume,' b"you're in your starched shirt, and you have your expensive hat on. you came" b'to ridicule the poor women and children who are lying on the floor, who are' b'already getting sick, whose relatives have died. did you come to laugh at' b'them?" and the one who was accompanying him, an azerbaijani, i don\'t know who' b"he was or what his title was, he quickly snatched the hat off muslimzade's head" b'and hid it. then i said, "my god! we\'re not marauders. we\'re not you! we' b'didn\'t come to you with the intention of stealing!" "well kill me, kill me!"' b'muslimzade says to me, "but i\'m not guilty kill me, kill me, but i\'m not' b'guilty." and i say, "ok, fine, you\'re not guilty, have it your way. but give' b"us an answer, we're asking you: where were you when they were torturing and" b'raping those poor women, when they were killing the children, burning things,' b'carrying on outrageously, and wrecking all those apartments? where were you' b'then?" "you know, we didn\'t expect it, we did not know what to do, we didn\'t' b'anticipate that something like that would happen in sumgait." i started' b'laughing and said, "it\'s truly funny." he says, "what could i do? we didn\'t' b'know what to do." and i say, "i\'m sorry, but it\'ll be ridiculous if i tell' b"you: the first secretary of the city party committee shouldn't march out in" b'front with a banner; he should fall down so that the gang would have to cross' b"over his dead body. that's what you should have done. that's the way it was" b'during the war. not a single party committee secretary compromised himself;' b'either he died or he led people into battle. and what did you do? you ran' b'away, you left, you hid, you marched with a flag, because you were afraid,' b'excuse my language, you feared for your own damned hide. and when we ask you,' b'you tell us that you got confused and you ask me what you could have done?' b'that\'s right," i told him, "the city party committee got confused, all the' b'party committees got confused, the police got confused,. baku got confused,' b'they all lay in a faint for two weeks, and the gang ran the show with' b"impunity. and if it weren't for the troops it wouldn't have been just two" b"days, there wouldn't be a single armenian left in sumgait for sure, they would" b'have finished their bloody affair, because they brazenly went up to some' b'russians, too, the ones who tried to say something to them, and they told' b'them, \'as soon as we finish with the armenians we\'ll come after you, too."' b'' b'and by the way, there was a colonel, who took us to the military unit. he was' b'the one with the light blue collar tabs who flew in and two hours later' b'arrived on an armored personnel carrier when we were at the sk and took us to' b'the military unit and who later started moving us from the military unit. we' b'asked him, "what? how? what will come of us?" he openly said, "you know, for' b"us the main thing now is to catch that gang. we'll finish that quickly. you'll" b'stay at the military unit for the time being, and we\'ll decide later." the' b'general procuracy of the ussr arrived, it consists of investigators from all' b'cities. there were some from stavropol, from everywhere, just everywhere, because' b'the affair was truly frightful. about this, by the way, comrade katusev spoke;' b"as everyone knows, he's the first deputy general procurator of the ussr. when" b'he gave us a speech from the armored personnel carrier at the military unit,' b"by the way, he told us the honest truth, because he couldn't not say it," b'because he was still experiencing his first impressions of what he had seen,' b'and he said, "there was afghanistan; and it was bad, but sumgait--it\'s' b'horrible! and the people who dared to do such a thing will be severely' b'punished, in accordance with our laws." and that\'s a quote. then one mother' b'throws herself at him--her two sons had died before her very eyes--and says,' b'"who will return my sons? who is going to punish the [culprits]?" they tried' b'to calm her down, and he said, "in order for us to conduct a proper' b'investigation, in order that not a single scoundrel avoid responsibility, you' b"must help us, because we don't know, maybe there was someone else in the gang" b'who is now being concealed in homes, and maybe the neighbors know, maybe' b"someone saw something. don't be afraid, write about it in detail. so that" b"you're not afraid everyone knows that many of you are afraid, having" b'lived through such horrors, they think that if they write the whole truth' b"about, let's say, their neighbor or someone else, that they will seek revenge" b"later. we're going to do it like this: we're going to set up an urn and you" b"can throw what you write in there. we don't need to know who wrote it. the" b"names of the people who write won't be made public, but we need all the" b'information. let each and every one not be afraid, let each write what is' b'necessary, who they saw in that gang, who made threats or shouted threatening' b'gibes about the armenians you must describe all of these people and put' b'the information into the urn."' b'' b'two soldiers and a major guarded the urn. and, sure enough, many people,' b"people who didn't even want to write .i know one woman who asked me, she" b'came up and said, "you, as a russian, the same thing won\'t happen to you as' b"will happen to me. so please i'll give you the information, and you" b'please write it down for me." so she was afraid, and there were a lot like' b'her but later, after katusev made his speech, she sat and wrote down' b"everything she knew. and we threw it all into the urn. now we don't know if" b'it will be of any use. for a factual picture will emerge from all that' b"information. one person can lie, but thousands can't lie, thousands simply" b"can't lie. you have to agree with that, a fact is a fact. why, for example," b'should someone say that black is white if it is really black?' b'' b'the first deputy chairman of the council of ministers of the azerbaijani' b'ssr, mamedov, as i said, was in yerevan. my husband and i were at the council' b'of ministers of the armenian ssr and found out that mamedov was present, the' b'one who had come to convince the people of sumgait to return to their' b'previous dwellings, to their old apartments. we asked for a meeting with him,' b'and it was granted. when we went to see him he tried to behave properly, very' b'politely, delicately, but when the truth was told right to his face and' b'when i asked him some of the same questions i had asked muslimzade, "where were' b"you personally when they were beating us? now you're trying to convince us to" b"return, why didn't you think at the time that they were slaughtering us where" b'it was all leading?" he says, "you\'re telling the truth. let\'s not mince' b"words. you've told me right to my face, and i'll tell you straight. i'll tell" b'you the pure truth. i was gotten out of bed in the evening, the whole' b'government was up, including me, and we were restraining a crowd of about' b'45,000 in baku. but we never expected that in a city like sumgait, with its' b'fine international record, such a thing could happen. we expected it in baku."' b'i say, "so that means you expected it all the same? why were you expecting' b'it?" and he says, "you know, it just happened that way. we were expecting it' b'in baku, we were trying to restrain it, but in sumgait i say, "fine,' b"you didn't know for the first three or four hours, but then you should have" b'known. why did no one help us?" and he says, "well, ok, we didn\'t know what to' b'do" and things like that. basically it was the same story i got from' b'muslimzade. later, when he said, "you go on back, the situation in sumgait is' b'favorable now, everything is fine, the armenians are friendly with the' b'azerbaijanis to this l answered, "you know what i\'m speaking' b'with you as a [member of a] neutral nation i have never argued with' b'armenians or with azerbaijanis and i was an eyewitness you tell me,' b'please, comrade mamedov, i asked him, "what would you say about this' b'honestly, if you were being completely frank with us?" then he said, "yes, i' b'admit that i am honestly ashamed, shame on the entire azerbaijani nation, we' b'have disgraced ourselves not only before the entire soviet union, but before' b'the whole world. because now the voice of america and all the other foreign' b'radio stations of various hues are branding us with all kinds of rumors, too."' b'and i say, "there\'s nothing to add to what really happened. i don\'t think it\'s' b'possible to add anything more awful." he says, "yes, i agree with you, i' b'understand your pain, it is truly an unfortunate occurrence." i repeat that he' b'said "unfortunate occurrence." and then he suddenly remembered himself, what' b'he was saying--he had a pen in his hands, he was fidgeting with it nervously--' b'and said, "oh, excuse me, a tragedy, really i take this to mean that' b'he really thinks it\'s an "unfortunate occurrence." "and of course," he says,' b'"i understand that having gone through all this you can\'t return to sumgait,' b"but it's necessary to cool down and realize that all those people are being" b'tried." and he even gave a detail, which, i don\'t know if it matters or not,' b'that policemen were being tried. specifically in relation to that bloody' b'affair.' b'' b'yes, by the way, there is another good detail, how i was set up at work in' b'baku after the events. i went to an undergarment plant, there was an' b'azerbaijani working there, and suddenly she tells me, "what, they didn\'t' b'nail your husband? they screwed up." i was floored, i hadn\'t imagined that' b'anyone in baku, too, could say something like that. well after that i went up' b'to see to my office, i needed to find out about those days, what was' b'going to happen with them, how they were going to put down those days from' b'february to march and the administrator told me, "i don\'t know,' b"tatyana, go to the head of the conductors' pool. be grateful if they don't" b'put it down as unexcused absence." i was really discouraged by this. they all' b'know that we were but a hair away from death and barely survived, and here' b"they're telling me that i was skipping work, as though i was off enjoying" b'myself somewhere. i went to the office of the chief of the pool, his last name' b"is rasulov, and he's had that position for many years. incidentally, he's a" b'party member, and is a big man in town. and suddenly, when i went to him and' b'said, "comrade rasulov, this is the way it was he looked at me askance' b'and said, "and why are you"--he knows me by my previous last name--"why did' b'you get wrapped up in this mess?" i say, "what do you mean, why did i get' b'wrapped up in this mess? my husband\'s an armenian," i tell him, "i have an' b'armenian last name." and he screwed up his face, made a kind of a grimace, as' b'though he had eaten something sour, and said, "i didn\'t expect that you would' b'. what did he mean by that? and "how" should he behave, the chief of the' b"pool, a man who supervises workers? now, it's true, there was a" b'reduction, but for sure there are still conductors working for him. and' b'if someone who supervises a staff that size says things like that, then what' b'can you expect from a simple, uneducated, politically unsophisticated person?!' b"he's going to believe any and all rumors, that the armenians are like this," b'the armenians are like that, and so on b'' b"by the way, that mamedov--now i'm going back to mamedov's office when i asked" b'him "are you really going to guarantee the safety of our lives if we return' b'to sumgait?" he answered, "yes, you know, i would guarantee them i don\'t' b'want to take on too much, i would guarantee them firmly for years. but i' b'won\'t guarantee them for longer than years." i say, "so you\'ve got another' b"thing like that planned for years from now? so they'll be quiet and then" b'in another years it\'ll happen again?!" i couldn\'t contain myself any more,' b'and i also told him, "and how did it get to that point, certainly you knew' b'about it, how they were treating the russians, for example, in baku and in' b'sumgait, how they were hounded from their jobs? certainly you received' b'complaints, i wrote some myself. why did no one respond to them? why did' b"everyone ignore what was going on? didn't you prepare people for this by the" b'way you treated them?" and he says, "you know, you\'re finally starting to' b'insult me!" he threw his pen on the desk. "maybe now you\'ll say i\'m a' b'scoundrel too?" i say, "you know, i\'m not talking about you because i don\'t' b'know. but about the ones who i do know i can say with conviction, yes, that' b'comrade was involved in this, that, and that, because i know for certain.' b'"well anyway he assured us that here, in yerevan, there were false rumors,' b'that sumgait armenians were here, and were in sumgait and had' b'gotten back to work. everyone was working, he said, and life was very good.' b'"we drove about the town ourselves, comrade arutiunian [first secretary of' b'the communist party of armenia ssr] came from the council of ministers of' b'armenian, he came and brought information showing that everything was fine in' b'sumgait." when i asked mamedov how he had reached that conclusion he said, b'"well, i walked down the street." and i said, "walking down the street in any' b'city, even if i were to go to new york, i would never understand the situation' b"because i would be a gues